        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/3/b38774/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2025-12-08T13:07:45.218Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Setting up Signal for Desktop requires using the phone app to scan the QR code on the desktop app. However, fully blind users do not know where to point their phone to scan the QR code.</p>\n<p>The QR code appears to contain a link device URL that contains a 24 byte base64-encoded UUID and 44-byte base64-encoded public key. I believe the best solution that doesn’t introduce additional security concerns is to show the UUID and public key as text on the desktop app and allow users to type the UUID and public key on the mobile app to link the devices.</p>\n<p>It’s also challenging to enter 68 base64 characters without mistakes (even for a fully sighted person) and it’d be helpful to convert the data into a phrase using a word list. If this approach is taken, I’d suggest the BIP 39 word list that has 2048 words. It avoids similar-sounding words which is helpful for screen readers. Based on my calculations (64^68 = 2048^x), it’d require typing 38 words total.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 3,
        "updated_at": "2025-12-08T13:07:45.218Z",
